{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NNwxN9YSK9r7ucT6brTFU5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the problem clearly now. In the ConfigMap `es-config`, the `node.name` setting is empty:\n```yaml\nnode.name: \n```\n\nThis is a \"null-valued setting\" error. The `node.name` is blank, which causes Elasticsearch to fail with `ElasticsearchParseException[null-valued setting found for key [node.name]]`.\n\nThe other nodes (es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1) are presumably working fine, which means they have a different configuration or the node.name is resolved differently for them.\n\nWait, looking at the ConfigMap - it's shared by all nodes. \n\nBut if es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 are running fine with the same ConfigMap, they must not have picked up the change yet. The ConfigMap is mounted as a volume, so the pods would need to be restarted or the volume would need to be remounted for them to see the updated empty value. That's why es-cluster-2 is failing—it's the first pod to start with the broken configuration.\n\nLooking at the seed hosts configuration, all three pods are listed as discovery seed hosts, which should help them find each other. But the actual error is about `node.name` being null, not about seed host discovery. Let me trace through how the pods are configured and whether they're all using the same ConfigMap or if there's something different about es-cluster-2's setup. I need to look at the StatefulSet definition to see how node.name is being configured—it might be set through an environment variable that's overriding what's in the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1753,"cache_read_input_tokens":30858,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1753},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"di